Why Pods Limit = 17
This is an AWS networking limitation.
Each Pod gets an IP from VPC CNI.
Maximum Pods depend on:


EC2 instance type


Number of ENIs


Secondary IPs per ENI


Example:


t3.medium → around 17 pods


t3.large → around 35 pods



Check Instance Type
Run:
kubectl get nodes -o wide
Then SSH into node:
curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/instance-type
Or:
kubectl describe node <node-name> | grep Instance
This helps map capacity to EC2 type.


------------

For a t2.medium node in Amazon EKS, maximum Pods are typically 17.

You can verify directly from Kubernetes:

kubectl describe node <node-name> | grep pods

Example:

kubectl describe node ip-192-168-0-38.ec2.internal | grep pods

Output:

pods: 17
Why Only 17 Pods?

AWS calculates pod limit using:

Number of ENIs (Elastic Network Interfaces)
IP addresses per ENI

Formula:

(Number of ENIs × (IPs per ENI - 1)) + 2

For t2.medium:

ENIs = 3
IPs per ENI = 6

So:

(3×(6−1))+2=17

Meaning:

Maximum Pods ≈ 17
Important

This is NOT mainly CPU/RAM limitation.

Even if CPU and memory are free, Kubernetes cannot schedule more Pods once:

Pod IPs are exhausted
ENI limits reached

