Even though only 1 application Pod is running, every node still consumes CPU and memory because Kubernetes system components are running on all worker nodes.

Why Other Nodes Still Show CPU Usage
Each node runs background components such as:


kubelet


kube-proxy


aws-node (VPC CNI)


container runtime


system daemons


monitoring agents


DNS/networking processes


These consume CPU even without your app Pods.
That’s why you see:
CPU% 1% to 6%
on all nodes.

Example
Your app Pod:
nginx-hpa-bb688f6fd-l69tl
is running only on:
ip-192-168-7-217
But other nodes still run Kubernetes infrastructure services.

Why Nodes Were NOT Removed Yet
Cluster Autoscaler/Karpenter does not instantly terminate nodes.
It waits because:


node may receive new Pods soon


avoids frequent EC2 creation/deletion


stabilization/cooldown period


Usually nodes stay idle for several minutes before removal.

Verify System Pods
Run:
kubectl get pods -A -o wide
You’ll notice on every node:


aws-node


kube-proxy


coredns


metrics-server
etc.


These are consuming the CPU you see.

Important Concept
Even an “empty” Kubernetes node is never truly empty.
A node always runs:


Kubernetes agents


networking stack


monitoring


OS services


So:


0 application Pods ❌


does NOT mean


0 CPU usage ❌



Ideally Should Only One Node Exist?
Theoretically yes — if:


autoscaler scale-down delay completes


node becomes drainable


no daemon constraints


autoscaler configured properly


Then unused nodes will terminate automatically.
You’re currently in the cooldown/stabilization period after HPA scaled down from 20 Pods → 1 Pod.


HPA increases Pods
        ↓
Scheduler needs more space
        ↓
Cluster Autoscaler increases Nodes
        ↓
Traffic decreases
        ↓
HPA decreases Pods
        ↓
ASG desired capacity still 4
        ↓
Nodes remain running



